entry.name: msinvalidurl
entry.text: Cannot create url '%s'
entry.description: The provided URL cannot be parsed. It is probably malformed.
entry.suggestion: Update the configuration or program to provide a valid URL.

entry.name: msactcomplete
entry.text: rule (%1$s): #%2$d %3$s completed OK.
entry.description: Indicates that the service completed the processing of an action from the current rule. You can use this message to track the progress of a transaction. If an action completes successfully, the service should proceed to the next action.

entry.name: msbadcontenttype
entry.text: Malformed Content-Type Header: %s
entry.description: The content-type header provided by the transport protocol (such as HTTP) was invalid. The content-type header must be parsed to decode MIME attachments (such as used with SOAP With Attachments). A correctly formed header would be: 'multipart/related; type="text/xml"; boundary="----=_Part"'
entry.suggestion: Ensure that the content-type header is correctly formed.

entry.name: msnocontenttype
entry.text: Protocol layer did not supply content-type
entry.description: The processing engine cannot find a content-type for this message. Certain protocols, such as MQ, might not provide a content-type unless properly configured. Others protocols, like HTTP, also provide one if there is a content-type included in the message.
entry.suggestion: If using HTTP, ensure that a content-type header is present in the request. If using MQ, ensure that your configuration is correct.

entry.name: msinvattachurl
entry.text: Invalid attachment url '%s'
entry.description: Attachment URLs allow access to the attachments connected to processing contexts. The submitted URL was improperly formed.
entry.suggestion: Ensure that the URL meets the specified format: attachment://<context>/<attachment-uri>

entry.name: msinvurl4fetch
entry.text: Cannot fetch '%1$s': no such context '%2$s'
entry.description: Attachment URLs allow access to the attachments connected to processing contexts. The submitted URL referenced a context that does not exist.
entry.suggestion: Check your configuration and the source of the URL for errors.

entry.name: mserrorrule
entry.text: rule (%1$s): failed - %2$s
entry.description: The error rule is invoked when a processing error occurs that would normally stop processing. This message indicates that an error occurred during the invocation of the error rule. Processing stopped.
entry.suggestion: Check your configuration. In particular, ensure that the specified error rule exists.

entry.name: msimplaction
entry.text: rule (%1$s): Implied action %2$s failed: %3$s
entry.description: In addition to actions configured in the rule, certain implied actions must also run. For example, an XML Firewall in SOAP mode will always insert an implied SOAP Envelope validity check that ensures the input is a well-formed SOAP message. This message indicates that one of the implied actions failed. Implied actions are inserted for the following reasons: SOAP Envelope checking; attachment processing; preservation of the INPUT context when used by multiple actions.
entry.suggestion: It is possible that the request was invalid. In which case, this message is expected. If not, the resolution depends on the specific type of implied action and the given reason for the failure.

entry.name: msactionerror
entry.description: An error occurred while processing an action in the current rule. The most probable cause is that the request is invalid, but an error in an XSLT stylesheet or bad configuration are also possibilities.
entry.suggestion: It is possible that the request is invalid. In which case, this log message is expected. If not the resolution depends on the specific type of action and the given reason for failure.

entry.name: msoutfiltered
entry.text: Output error text filtered to prevent possible cross-site scripting vulnerabilities. Original error text: %s
entry.description: The original error text contained an HTML <SCRIPT> tag. To avoid a possible cross-site scripting vulnerability, the original error text has been replaced with a known safe message. The original error text is reported in the log entry.

entry.name: msunknownpi
entry.text: XSL PI: ignoring unknown PI
entry.description: While scanning for the <?xml-stylesheet?> processing instruction, a processing instruction with another name was encountered and ignored.
entry.suggestion: No action necessary.

entry.name: msduplicatepi
entry.text: XSL PI already specified
entry.description: Two or more processing instructions named <?xml-stylesheet?> were encountered. Only the first processing instruction will be used.
entry.suggestion: Modify the input so that it contains only one <xml-stylesheet> processing instruction.

entry.name: msmaxinputdrain
entry.text: Drain input: exceeded maximum bytes. Drained %1$zd, max %2$zd
entry.description: The configuration of the processing policy never used the "INPUT" context, and so the service is ignoring the provided data. In the process, more data than the configured maximum size of input messages were encountered.
entry.suggestion: Raise the maximum size of input messages, or, if the size is correct, no action is necessary.

entry.name: msnostripattach
entry.text: Cannot strip attachment '%1$s': context '%2$s' has no attachments
entry.description: The strip-attachment action failed to remove attachments from the specified processing context, because no attachment was found.
entry.suggestion: If attachments were expected, check that the input message contained them. Check whether the service is configured to strip attachments from incoming messages by default.

entry.name: xpldocfuncerror
entry.text: Document function error while processing %1$s: %2$s
entry.description: A call to the XSLT document() function failed during a transformation. This message can be due to a failure to locate the document at a given URL, an I/O error while retrieving the document, or a syntax error while parsing the document as XML.
entry.suggestion: Examine other log messages near this one to determine the cause of the problem. If the cause is a failure to find a document at the given URL, it might indicate a bug in the XSLT, for example, a mistake in an XPath expression passed as an argument to document() function. If the cause is an I/O error or an XML syntax error, the problem is external to the DataPower Gateway.

entry.name: xslssheetabort
entry.text: Processing of '%1$s' stopped: %2$s
entry.description: An error was found during an XSLT transformation.
entry.suggestion: The log message details the location and nature of the XSLT error. If it is an error in the XSLT stylesheet itself, correct the problem there. Otherwise, the cause of the error might be in the input to the transformation; for example, the structure of the input XML might not conform to that expected by the stylesheet.

entry.description: Initialize Processing Metadata to get or set a variable or header for the corresponding protocol services.

entry.name: novariable
entry.text: dp:get-metadata: The variable '%s' is not available.
entry.description: The Processing Metadata is asked to return the value of a variable. However, that variable is either unknown or unsupported by the protocol.
entry.suggestion: Make sure the variable name, if it is in a custom category, is correct. Not every variable is supported by every protocol. It is normal for this message to occur for one protocol.

entry.name: noxmlparent
entry.text: dp:get-metadata: The metadata item '%1$s' cannot parse element '%2$s' with a non-XML parent metadata '%3$s'.
entry.description: When a metadata item is of the XML sub-node type, it depends on a parent metadata item. The parent metadata item is available, but it is not allowed to be used as an XML nodeset.
entry.suggestion: If the parent metadata item is a custom header or variable, make sure it has well-formed XML contents and contains a child element for the current item. Get the parent metadata item directly by using dp:get-metadata, and check its format. Contact IBM Support if you suspect this is a real error.

entry.name: noparent
entry.text: dp:get-metadata: The metadata item '%1$s' tries to use a sub-element '%2$s' for a nonexistent parent metadata item.
entry.description: When a metadata item is of the XML sub-node type, it depends on a parent metadata item. The parent metadata item is either unknown or not configured by the system.
entry.suggestion: Contact IBM Support.

entry.name: cannotparse
entry.text: Cannot parse the metadata item '%1$s' into a nodeset. Error "%2$s".
entry.description: The Processing Metadata item is available but invalid for use as an XML nodeset.
entry.suggestion: If the metadata item is a custom header or variable, ensure that it has well-formed XML contents. This error does not cause any problems for the current metadata item, but it could make any sub-node metadata items unavailable. If this is a system metadata item, ensure that its value is not modified by prior services.

entry.description: Obtaining the value from a header or variable.

entry.name: badcategory

entry.name: ignoreitem

entry.name: readall

entry.description: All the default metadata items with non-empty values will be returned.
entry.suggestion: If you only want to get specific metadata items, define a Processing Metadata configuration and pass in the object name for dp:get-metadata().

entry.name: setnonexisting

entry.description: Attempted to overwrite, append, or delete a metadata item that does not exist for the current protocol.
entry.suggestion: Ensure that the input metadata XML document contains the correct element names.

entry.name: setnotallowed

entry.description: Cannot overwrite, append, or delete this metadata item.

entry.name: setheaderitem
entry.text: dp:set-metadata: Update header '%1$s' for the protocol '%2$s'.
entry.description: If the header does not exist then a new header will be created, otherwise the old value will be replaced with the input data.

entry.name: setvaritem
entry.text: dp:set-metadata: Update variable '%1$s' for the protocol '%2$s'.
entry.description: If the variable does not exist then a new variable will be created, otherwise the old value will be replaced with the input data.

entry.name: noappend
entry.text: Not allowed to append variable '%s', will try to directly overwrite variable.
entry.description: The input metadata item value cannot be appended to a variable, it will be used to replace the existing value.
entry.suggestion: Modify the input metadata item to use the "overwrite" action instead.

entry.name: nodelete
entry.text: dp:set-metadata: Not allowed to delete variable '%s', no action is taken.
entry.description: After a variable is created for the service or context, it cannot be deleted.
entry.suggestion: Modify the input metadata item to use the proper action instead.

entry.name: cannotsetvar
entry.text: dp:set-metadata: The variable '%s' is not set successfully.
entry.description: The variable is either invalid, unsupported, or not writable for the current protocol service.
entry.suggestion: If the metadata item is a custom variable, ensure that its name is correct and that this protocol service supports this writable variable.

entry.name: unknownitemtype
entry.text: Unknown type %1$d' is detected for metadata item '%2$s'.
entry.description: The metadata item type is unknown. The newer configuration cannot be used for the old releases.
entry.suggestion: Contact IBM to solve this problem, the following data will be helpful: product release version, protocol services and configuration, Processing Metadata Category, and this error message.

entry.name: cannotparseresult
entry.text: dp:get-metadata: Cannot parse the result into nodeset. Error "%s".
entry.description: The metadata item is a parent item for other metadata items. Those metadata items expect this parent item to contain corresponding XML child elements. However, the text value for this metadata item cannot be parsed into an XML document.
entry.suggestion: Contact IBM Support.

entry.name: noinputnodeset
entry.text: dp:set-metadata: Input nodeset is null, nothing to do.
entry.description: The dp:set-metadata XSLT extension element contains no data to set.
entry.suggestion: Check the input nodeset with the dp:set-metadata extension element.

entry.name: unknownprotocol
entry.text: The protocol '%s' is not recognized or invalid, only the customizable metadata items will be checked.
entry.description: There is no metadata category corresponding to this protocol scheme. No system metadata items are configured for any services in this protocol. Only the custom header or variable categories will be supported for this protocol.
entry.suggestion: Ensure that the protocol service has set a value for "var://service/protocol", and a metadata category was configured for this protocol.

entry.name: conflictaction
entry.text: dp:set-metadata: The metadata item '%1$s' is ignored because its action conflicts with the action of its parent metadata item '%2$s'.
entry.description: The input metadata document contains two metadata items. One metadata item is a sub-element of the other metadata item. However, the action attributes for the two metadata items are not same.
entry.suggestion: Check the input metadata XML document and correct the action attributes for one of the elements in question.

entry.name: incompatiblestylesheet
entry.text: Binary stylesheet %1$s is incompatible with non-binary processing action %2$s
entry.description: The processing action is of a non-binary type, but it references a binary stylesheet containing DataGlue instructions.
entry.suggestion: This error is usually due to a misconfiguration. Change the action type or change the stylesheet.

entry.name: attachmodeconflict
entry.text: Unprocessed attachment mode is incompatible with XPath dispatch
entry.description: Cannot perform unprocessed attachment mode processing. This mode is incompatible with certain service configurations.
entry.suggestion: Change the attachment processing mode to Strip or Allow.

entry.name: pipeoutputconflict
entry.text: Action output to PIPE cannot work with next action input
entry.description: Cannot output the data to the pipe. The next action cannot process streaming data.
entry.suggestion: Change the action output to be another context or change the input of the next action to PIPE.

entry.name: skipdownrule
entry.text: Rule Skipped: match '%1$s' matches but rule '%2$s' is down
entry.description: The matching criteria of the rule matched the transactional context, but processing of rule was skipped due to down operational state. The most likely cause is an invalid processing action.
entry.suggestion: Examine the status of the processing rule to identify the invalid processing action.

entry.name: extrejectset

entry.description: The extension function dp:reject was set in the context of a filter or transform action. It will overwrite any previous invocation of dp:accept. If @override is set, it will also overwrite the reason of any previous call to dp:reject or dp:send-error. Otherwise the reason of only the first dp:reject or dp:send-error invocation is retained. If not overwritten with dp:accept, processing will be stopped after the completion of this action.

entry.name: extsenderror

If @override is set, it will also overwrite the reason of any previous call to dp:reject or dp:send-error. Otherwise the reason of only the first dp:reject or dp:send-error invocation is retained. If not overwritten with dp:accept, processing will be stopped after the completion of this action.

entry.name: evsinknoaction

entry.description: The event-sink action requires the name of an action to wait for, but an empty action name was found in the event-sink action list, possibly as the result of resolving a context variable.
entry.suggestion: If a var://context/ctx/var context variable name is in the event-sink action list, ensure that this variable contains the name of an action.

entry.name: evsinkdoesnotexist

entry.name: evsinksyncaction

entry.suggestion: Check that the event-sink action is waiting for the correct action, and that the actions it is waiting for are marked as asynchronous.

entry.description: One of the actions an event-sink is waiting for did not complete in the timeout specified on the event-sink.
entry.suggestion: Make the timeout on the event-sink action longer.

entry.name: evsinknotstarted
entry.text: Event-sink timed out: event-sink action never ran.
entry.description: One of the actions an event-sink is waiting for did not start in the timeout specified on the event-sink.
entry.suggestion: Make sure the named action actually runs in the policy; or make the timeout on the event-sink action longer.

entry.name: loop_xpath_not_nodeset

Check the input to the XPath with the probe or send it back to the client to try to understand what output resulted and why that output is not a node set. For example, an XML Firewall in SOAP mode will always insert an implied SOAP Envelope validity check that ensures the input is a well-formed SOAP message. This message indicates that one of the implied actions failed. Implied actions are inserted for the following reasons: SOAP Envelope checking; attachment processing; preservation of the INPUT context when used by multiple actions.
entry.suggestion: It is possible that the request was invalid. In which case, this message is expected. If not, the resolution depends on the specific type of implied action and the given reason for the failure.
